column5: How can we find out if the ID NOW test offered by Walgreens is an accepted test. According to Abbott Labs.... Genetic Testing COVID-19 Testing Infectious Disease Testing Company Abbott ID NOW Rapid Molecular Test (NAAT) I would hate to get to the border and they say only the PCR test is valid. What say you OBABIKON??? You seem to be pretty proactive. Thansk ahead of time.

I went to Walgreens yesterday and the pharmacist said they have the test I need and it take 72 hours to get it back, then I showed him the accepted tests and said he has them that takes 6-24 hours to get them back. Also, forgot to ask how much so if you know please share.

I talked to our resort owner today and he said as long as it is not a antigen test I'll be good to go. He was just down here last week and went to a CVS and took his test. 24 hrs and he had the results. He said Walgreens has them also.

Here's a list from Canadian Govt. website- hese tests are considered acceptable molecular tests: (The 4th one down is the NAAT) PCR - Polymerase chain reaction RT-PCR Â– reverse transcription real time PCR Quantitative PCR (qPCR) Nucleic acid test (NAT) or Nucleic acid amplification test (NAATs) Reverse transcription loop-mediated isothermal amplification (RT-LAMP) Isothermal amplification Droplet digital PCR or digital droplet PCR (ddPCR) Transcription-mediated amplification (TMA) RNA (Ribonucleic acid) Ct (cycle threshold) CRISPR Sequencing Next generational sequencing (NGS) or whole genome sequencing (WGS) Oxford Nanopore sequencing (LamPORE) Detection of the N gene Detection of Orf1a/b Detection of the S gene Detection of the E gene Detection of the RdRp gene This came from a link posted by ADempsy in this forum
